1
00:00:00,210 --> 00:00:04,040
CHAPTER ONE
Thunder Road - Bruce Spingsteen

2
00:00:04,040 --> 00:00:09,980
I can remember listening to this song and
loving it in 1975; I can remember listening

3
00:00:09,980 --> 00:00:14,450
to this song and loving it almost as much
quite recently, a few months ago.

4
00:00:14,450 --> 00:00:20,140
(And, yes, I was in a car, although I probably
wasn't driving, and I certainly wasn't driving

5
00:00:20,140 --> 00:00:26,599
down any turnpike or highway or freeway, and
the wind wasn't blowing through my hair, because

6
00:00:26,599 --> 00:00:29,619
I possess neither a convertible nor hair.

7
00:00:29,619 --> 00:00:31,999
It's not that version of Springsteen.)

8
00:00:31,999 --> 00:00:37,570
So I've loved this song for a quarter of a
century now, and I've heard it more than anything

9
00:00:37,570 --> 00:00:39,820
else, with the possible exception of...

10
00:00:39,820 --> 00:00:41,590
Who am I kidding?

11
00:00:41,590 --> 00:00:43,239
There are no other contenders.

12
00:00:43,239 --> 00:00:49,570
See, what I was going to do there was soften
the blow, slip in something black and... or

13
00:00:49,570 --> 00:00:54,989
cool possibly 'Let's Get It On', which I think
is the best pop record ever made, and which

14
00:00:54,989 --> 00:01:01,020
would easily make it into my top 20 most-played
songs list, but not at number 2.

15
00:01:01,020 --> 00:01:05,570
Number 2 - and I'm trying to be honest here
- would probably be something like '(White

16
00:01:05,570 --> 00:01:11,280
Man) In Hammersmith Palais' by The Clash,
but it would be way, way behind.

17
00:01:11,280 --> 00:01:17,270
Let's say I've played 'Thunder Road' 1,500
times (just over once a week for twenty-five

18
00:01:17,270 --> 00:01:21,799
years, which sounds about right, if one takes
into account the repeat plays in the first

19
00:01:21,799 --> 00:01:27,330
couple of years); '(White Man)... would have
clocked up something like 500 plays.

20
00:01:27,330 --> 00:01:30,530
In other words, there's no real competition.

21
00:01:30,530 --> 00:01:36,450
It's weird to me how 'Thunder Road' has survived
when so many other, arguably better songs

22
00:01:36,450 --> 00:01:42,799
- 'Maggie May', 'Hey Jude', 'God Save The
Queen', 'Stir It Up', 'So Tired of Being Alone',

23
00:01:42,799 --> 00:01:47,479
'You're A Big Girl Now' - have become less
compelling as I've got older.

24
00:01:47,479 --> 00:01:53,520
It's not as if I can't see the flaws: 'Thunder
Road' is overwrought, both lyrically (as Prefab

25
00:01:53,520 --> 00:01:58,850
Sprout pointed out, there's more to life than
cars and girls, and surely the word 'redemption'

26
00:01:58,850 --> 00:02:04,189
is to be avoided like the plague when you're
writing songs about redemption) and musically

27
00:02:04,189 --> 00:02:09,500
- after all, this four and three-quarter minutes
provided Jim Steinman and Meatloaf with a

28
00:02:09,500 --> 00:02:10,960
whole career.

29
00:02:10,960 --> 00:02:17,250
It's also po-faced, in a way that Springsteen
himself isn't, and if the doomed romanticism

30
00:02:17,250 --> 00:02:22,670
wasn't corny in 1975, then it certainly is
now.

31
00:02:22,670 --> 00:02:29,040
But sometimes, very occasionally, songs and
books and films and pictures express who you

32
00:02:29,040 --> 00:02:31,020
are, perfectly.

33
00:02:31,020 --> 00:02:35,530
And they don't do this in words or images,
necessarily; the connection is a lot less

34
00:02:35,530 --> 00:02:38,920
direct and more complicated than that.

35
00:02:38,920 --> 00:02:44,150
When I was first beginning to write seriously,
I read Anne Tyler's Dinner at the Homesick

36
00:02:44,150 --> 00:02:50,510
Restaurant, and suddenly knew what I was,
and what I wanted to be, for better or for

37
00:02:50,510 --> 00:02:51,510
worse.

38
00:02:51,510 --> 00:02:53,800
It's a process something like falling in love.

39
00:02:53,800 --> 00:02:59,471
You don't necessarily choose the best person,
or the wisest, or the most beautiful; there's

40
00:02:59,471 --> 00:03:01,630
something else going on.

41
00:03:01,630 --> 00:03:07,150
There was a part of me that would rather have
fallen for Updike, or Kerouac, or DeLillo

42
00:03:07,150 --> 00:03:12,430
- for someone masculine, at least, maybe somebody
a little more opaque, and certainly someone

43
00:03:12,430 --> 00:03:17,780
who uses more swear-words - and, though I
have admired those writers, at various stages

44
00:03:17,780 --> 00:03:22,890
in my life, admiration is a very different
thing from the kind of transference I'm talking

45
00:03:22,890 --> 00:03:24,010
about.

46
00:03:24,010 --> 00:03:29,180
I'm talking about understanding - or at least
feeling like I understand - every artistic

47
00:03:29,180 --> 00:03:33,940
decision, every impulse, the soul of both
the work and its creator.

48
00:03:33,940 --> 00:03:39,500
'This is me,' I wanted to say when I read
Tyler's rich, sad, lovely novel.

49
00:03:39,500 --> 00:03:44,950
'I'm not a character, I'm nothing like the
author, I haven't had the experiences she

50
00:03:44,950 --> 00:03:46,050
writes about.

51
00:03:46,050 --> 00:03:49,950
But even so, this is what I feel like, inside.

52
00:03:49,950 --> 00:03:54,740
This is what I would sound like, if ever I
were to find a voice.'

53
00:03:54,740 --> 00:04:01,450
And I did find a voice, eventually, and it
was mine, not hers; but nevertheless, so powerful

54
00:04:01,450 --> 00:04:06,350
was the process of identification that I still
don't feel as though I've expressed myself

55
00:04:06,350 --> 00:04:11,340
as well, as completely, as Tyler did on my
behalf then.

56
00:04:11,340 --> 00:04:17,729
So, even though I'm not American, no longer
young, hate cars, and can recognize why so

57
00:04:17,729 --> 00:04:23,930
many people find Springsteen bombastic and
histrionic (but not why they find him macho

58
00:04:23,930 --> 00:04:29,590
or jingoistic or dumb - that kind of ignorant
judgment has plagued Springsteen for a huge

59
00:04:29,590 --> 00:04:34,410
part of his career, and is made by smart people
who are actually a lot dumber than he has

60
00:04:34,410 --> 00:04:39,500
ever been), 'Thunder Road' somehow manages
to speak for me.

61
00:04:39,500 --> 00:04:45,699
This is partly - and perhaps shamingly - because
a lot of Springsteen's songs from this period

62
00:04:45,699 --> 00:04:51,540
are about becoming famous, or at least achieving
some kind of public validation through his

63
00:04:51,540 --> 00:04:56,099
art: what else are we supposed to think when
the last line of the song is 'I'm pulling

64
00:04:56,099 --> 00:05:01,800
out of here to win', other than that he has
won, simply by virtue of playing the song,

65
00:05:01,800 --> 00:05:06,100
night after night after night, to an ever-increasing
crowd of people?

66
00:05:06,100 --> 00:05:11,169
(And what else are we supposed to think when
in 'Rosalita' he sings, with a touching, funny

67
00:05:11,169 --> 00:05:17,259
and innocent glee, 'Cos the record company,
Rosie, just gave me a big advance', other

68
00:05:17,259 --> 00:05:21,500
than that the record company has just given
him a big advance?)

69
00:05:21,500 --> 00:05:27,620
It's never objectionable or obnoxious, this
dream of fame, because it derives from a restless

70
00:05:27,620 --> 00:05:34,009
and uncontrollable artistic urge - he knows
he has talent to burn, and the proper reward

71
00:05:34,009 --> 00:05:39,449
for this, he seems to suggest, would be the
financial wherewithal to fulfil it - rather

72
00:05:39,449 --> 00:05:42,380
than an interest in celebrity for its own
sake.

73
00:05:42,380 --> 00:05:47,909
Hosting a TV quiz show, or assassinating a
president, wouldn't scratch the itch at all.

74
00:05:47,909 --> 00:05:52,419
And, of course - don't let anyone tell you
otherwise - if you have dreams of becoming

75
00:05:52,419 --> 00:05:58,810
a writer, then there are murky, mucky visions
of fame attached to these dreams too; 'Thunder

76
00:05:58,810 --> 00:06:04,289
Road' was my answer to every rejection letter
I received, and every doubt expressed by friends

77
00:06:04,289 --> 00:06:05,430
or relatives.

78
00:06:05,430 --> 00:06:11,840
They lived in towns for losers, I told myself,
and I, like Bruce, was pulling out of there

79
00:06:11,840 --> 00:06:12,840
to win.

80
00:06:12,840 --> 00:06:18,490
(These towns, incidentally, were Cambridge
- full of loser doctors and lawyers and academics

81
00:06:18,490 --> 00:06:24,560
- and London - full of loser successes of
every description - but never mind.

82
00:06:24,560 --> 00:06:28,499
This was the material I had to work with,
and work with it I did.)

83
00:06:28,499 --> 00:06:33,099
It helped a great deal that, as time went
by, and there was no sign of me pulling out

84
00:06:33,099 --> 00:06:38,590
of anywhere to do anything very much, and
certainly not with the speed implied in the

85
00:06:38,590 --> 00:06:44,889
song, 'Thunder Road' made reference to age,
thus accommodating this lack of forward momentum.

86
00:06:44,889 --> 00:06:49,849
'So you're scared and you're thinking that
maybe we ain't that young any more', Bruce

87
00:06:49,849 --> 00:06:54,449
sang, and that line worked for me even when
I had begun to doubt whether there was any

88
00:06:54,449 --> 00:06:59,979
magic in the night: I continued thinking I
wasn't that young any more for a long, long

89
00:06:59,979 --> 00:07:05,919
time - decades, in fact - and even today I
choose to interpret it as a wistful observation

90
00:07:05,919 --> 00:07:11,550
of middle age, rather than the sharp fear
that comes on in late youth.

91
00:07:11,550 --> 00:07:17,259
It also helped that, sometime in the early
to mid-eighties, I came across another version

92
00:07:17,259 --> 00:07:22,300
of the song, a bootleg studio recording of
Springsteen alone with an acoustic guitar

93
00:07:22,300 --> 00:07:29,559
(it's on War And Roses, the Born To Run outtakes
bootleg); he reimagines 'Thunder Road' as

94
00:07:29,559 --> 00:07:36,189
a haunting, exhausted hymn to the past, to
lost love and missed opportunities and self-delusion

95
00:07:36,189 --> 00:07:41,520
and bad luck and failure, and that worked
pretty well for me, too.

96
00:07:41,520 --> 00:07:46,400
In fact, when I try to hear that last line
of the song in my head, it's the acoustic

97
00:07:46,400 --> 00:07:48,229
version that comes first.

98
00:07:48,229 --> 00:07:55,360
It's slow, and mournful, and utterly convincing:
an artist who can persuade you of the truth

99
00:07:55,360 --> 00:08:01,749
of what he is singing with either version
is an artist who is capable of an awful lot.

100
00:08:01,749 --> 00:08:05,319
There are other bootleg versions that I play
and love.

101
00:08:05,319 --> 00:08:10,199
One of the great things about the song as
it appears on Born To Run is that those first

102
00:08:10,199 --> 00:08:16,509
few bars, on wheezy harmonica and achingly
pretty piano, actually sound like they refer

103
00:08:16,509 --> 00:08:21,830
to something that has already happened before
the beginning of the record, something momentous

104
00:08:21,830 --> 00:08:28,360
and sad but not destructive of all hope; as
Thunder Road' is the first track on side one

105
00:08:28,360 --> 00:08:34,310
of Born To Run, the album begins, in effect,
with its own closing credits.

106
00:08:34,310 --> 00:08:39,970
In performance at the end of the seventies,
during the Darkness on the Edge of Town tour,

107
00:08:39,970 --> 00:08:45,370
Springsteen maximized this effect by seguing
into 'Thunder Road' out of one of his bleakest,

108
00:08:45,370 --> 00:08:50,750
most desperate songs, 'Racing In The Street',
and the harmonica that marks the transformation

109
00:08:50,750 --> 00:08:57,230
of one song into the other feels like a sudden
and glorious hint of spring after a long,

110
00:08:57,230 --> 00:08:58,780
withering winter.

111
00:08:58,780 --> 00:09:04,430
On the bootlegs of those seventies shows,
Thunder Road' can finally provide the salvation

112
00:09:04,430 --> 00:09:08,270
that its position on Born To Run denied it.

113
00:09:08,270 --> 00:09:13,880
Maybe the reason Thunder Road' has sustained
for me is that, despite its energy and volume

114
00:09:13,880 --> 00:09:20,270
and fast cars and hair, it somehow manages
to sound elegiac, and the older I get the

115
00:09:20,270 --> 00:09:22,050
more I can hear that.

116
00:09:22,050 --> 00:09:28,180
When it comes down to it, I suppose that I
too believe that life is momentous and sad

117
00:09:28,180 --> 00:09:33,520
but not destructive of all hope, and maybe
that makes me a self-dramatizing depressive,

118
00:09:33,520 --> 00:09:40,010
or maybe it makes me a happy idiot, but either
way 'Thunder Road' knows how I feel and who

119
00:09:40,010 --> 00:09:47,450
I am, and that, in the end, is one of the
consolations of art.

120
00:09:47,450 --> 00:09:49,010
Postscript

121
00:09:49,010 --> 00:09:55,350
A few years ago, I started to sell a lot of
books, at first only in the UK, and then later

122
00:09:55,350 --> 00:10:00,840
in other countries too, and to my intense
bewilderment found that I had somehow become

123
00:10:00,840 --> 00:10:04,140
part of the literary and cultural mainstream.

124
00:10:04,140 --> 00:10:07,820
It wasn't something I had expected, or was
prepared for.

125
00:10:07,820 --> 00:10:12,770
Although I could see no reason why anyone
would feel excluded from my work - it wasn't

126
00:10:12,770 --> 00:10:18,090
like it was difficult, or experimental - my
books still seemed to me to be quirky and

127
00:10:18,090 --> 00:10:19,940
small- scale.

128
00:10:19,940 --> 00:10:26,040
But suddenly all sorts of people, people I
didn't know or like or respect, had opinions

129
00:10:26,040 --> 00:10:32,940
about me and my work, which overnight seemed
to go from being fresh and original to cliched

130
00:10:32,940 --> 00:10:37,400
and ubiquitous, without a word of it having
changed.

131
00:10:37,400 --> 00:10:42,840
And I was shown this horrible reflection of
myself and what I did, a funfair hall-of-mirrors

132
00:10:42,840 --> 00:10:48,050
reflection, all squished-up and distorted
- me, but not me.

133
00:10:48,050 --> 00:10:52,671
It wasn't like I was given a particularly
hard time, and certainly other people, some

134
00:10:52,671 --> 00:10:55,680
of whom I know, have experienced much worse.

135
00:10:55,680 --> 00:11:01,910
But even so, it becomes in those circumstances
very hard to hang on to the idea of what you

136
00:11:01,910 --> 00:11:03,860
want to do.

137
00:11:03,860 --> 00:11:07,510
And yet Springsteen somehow managed to find
a way through.

138
00:11:07,510 --> 00:11:12,800
His name is still taken in vain frequently
(a year or so ago I read a newspaper piece

139
00:11:12,800 --> 00:11:18,550
attacking Tony Blair for his love of Bruce,
an indication, apparently, of the Prime Minister's

140
00:11:18,550 --> 00:11:23,940
incorrigible philistinism), and for some,
the hall-of-mirrors reflection is the only

141
00:11:23,940 --> 00:11:25,980
Springsteen they can see.

142
00:11:25,980 --> 00:11:32,000
He went from being rock 'n' roll future to
a lumpy, flag-waving, stadium-rocking meathead

143
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:37,860
in the space of a few months, again with nothing
much having changed, beyond the level of his

144
00:11:37,860 --> 00:11:39,100
popularity.

145
00:11:39,100 --> 00:11:45,510
Anyway, his strength of purpose, and the way
he has survived the assault on his sense of

146
00:11:45,510 --> 00:11:51,750
self, seem to me exemplary; sometimes it's
hard to remember that a lot of people liking

147
00:11:51,750 --> 00:11:58,220
what you do doesn't necessarily mean that
what you do is of no value whatsoever.

148
00:11:58,220 --> 00:12:02,380
Indeed, sometimes it might even suggest the
opposite.

149
00:12:02,380 --> 00:12:07,491
CHAPTER TWO
I'm Like a Bird - Nelly Furtado

150
00:12:07,491 --> 00:12:12,360
Oh, of course I can understand people dismissing
pop music.

151
00:12:12,360 --> 00:12:18,260
I know that a lot of it, nearly all of it,
is trashy, unimaginative, poorly written,

152
00:12:18,260 --> 00:12:24,230
slickly produced, inane, repetitive and juvenile
(although at least four of these adjectives

153
00:12:24,230 --> 00:12:29,440
could be used to describe the incessant attacks
on pop that you can still find in posh magazines

154
00:12:29,440 --> 00:12:36,220
and newspapers); I know too, believe me, that
Cole Porter was 'better' than Madonna or Travis,

155
00:12:36,220 --> 00:12:40,790
that most pop songs are aimed cynically at
a target audience three decades younger than

156
00:12:40,790 --> 00:12:46,080
I am, that in any case the golden age was
thirty-five years ago and there has been very

157
00:12:46,080 --> 00:12:48,170
little of value since.

158
00:12:48,170 --> 00:12:53,370
It's just that there's this song I heard on
the radio, and I bought the CD, and now I

159
00:12:53,370 --> 00:12:57,030
have to hear it ten or fifteen times a day...

160
00:12:57,030 --> 00:13:01,720
That's the thing that puzzles me about those
who feel that contemporary pop (and I use

161
00:13:01,720 --> 00:13:07,440
the word to encompass soul, reggae, country,
rock - anything and everything that might

162
00:13:07,440 --> 00:13:13,950
be regarded as trashy) is beneath them, or
behind them, or beyond them - some preposition

163
00:13:13,950 --> 00:13:19,310
denoting distance, anyway: does this mean
that you never hear, or at least never enjoy,

164
00:13:19,310 --> 00:13:25,190
new songs, that everything you whistle or
hum was written years, decades, centuries

165
00:13:25,190 --> 00:13:26,190
ago?

166
00:13:26,190 --> 00:13:31,550
Do you really deny yourselves the pleasure
of mastering a tune (a pleasure, incidentally,

167
00:13:31,550 --> 00:13:36,660
that your generation is perhaps the first
in the history of mankind to forgo) because

168
00:13:36,660 --> 00:13:41,160
you are afraid it might make you look as if
you don't know who Harold Bloom is?

169
00:13:41,160 --> 00:13:44,320
Wow, I'll bet you're fun at parties.

170
00:13:44,320 --> 00:13:50,990
The song that has been driving me pleasurably
potty recently is 'I'm Like a Bird' by Nelly

171
00:13:50,990 --> 00:13:51,990
Furtado.

172
00:13:51,990 --> 00:13:57,330
Only history will judge whether Ms Furtado
turns out to be any kind of artist, and though

173
00:13:57,330 --> 00:14:01,830
I have my suspicions that she will not change
the way we look at the world, I can't say

174
00:14:01,830 --> 00:14:07,700
that I'm very bothered: I will always be grateful
to her for creating in me the narcotic need

175
00:14:07,700 --> 00:14:10,330
to hear her song again and again.

176
00:14:10,330 --> 00:14:15,660
It is, after all, a harmless need, easily
satisfied, and there are few enough of those

177
00:14:15,660 --> 00:14:16,780
in the world.

178
00:14:16,780 --> 00:14:21,320
I don't even want to make a case for this
song, as opposed to any other - although I

179
00:14:21,320 --> 00:14:26,450
happen to think that it's a very good pop
song, with a dreamy languor and a bruised

180
00:14:26,450 --> 00:14:32,010
optimism that immediately distinguishes it
from its anemic and stunted peers.

181
00:14:32,010 --> 00:14:37,190
The point is that a few months ago it didn't
exist, at least as far as we are concerned,

182
00:14:37,190 --> 00:14:42,470
and now here it is, and that, in itself, is
a small miracle.

183
00:14:42,470 --> 00:14:47,660
Dave Eggers has a theory that we play songs
over and over, those of us who do, because

184
00:14:47,660 --> 00:14:53,140
we have to 'solve' them, and it's true that
in our early relationship with, and courtship

185
00:14:53,140 --> 00:14:59,350
of, a new song, there is a stage which is
akin to a sort of emotional puzzlement.

186
00:14:59,350 --> 00:15:03,701
There's a little bit in 'I'm Like a Bird',
for example, about halfway through, where

187
00:15:03,701 --> 00:15:08,160
the voice is double-tracked on a phrase, and
the effect - especially on someone who is

188
00:15:08,160 --> 00:15:14,510
not a musician, someone who loves and appreciates
music but is baffled and seduced by even the

189
00:15:14,510 --> 00:15:18,740
simplest musical tricks - is rich and fresh
and addictive.

190
00:15:18,740 --> 00:15:22,880
Sure, it will seem thin and stale soon enough.

191
00:15:22,880 --> 00:15:27,050
Before very long I will have 'solved' 'I'm
Like a Bird', and I won't want to hear it

192
00:15:27,050 --> 00:15:31,780
very much anymore - a three-minute pop song
can only withhold its mysteries for so long,

193
00:15:31,780 --> 00:15:32,780
after all.

194
00:15:32,780 --> 00:15:38,130
So, yes, it's disposable, as if that makes
any difference to anyone's perceptions of

195
00:15:38,130 --> 00:15:39,720
the value of pop music.

196
00:15:39,720 --> 00:15:43,800
But then, shouldn't we be sick of 'Moonlight'
Sonata by now?

197
00:15:43,800 --> 00:15:45,180
Or Christina's World?

198
00:15:45,180 --> 00:15:47,430
Or The Importance of Being Earnest?

199
00:15:47,430 --> 00:15:48,510
They're empty!

200
00:15:48,510 --> 00:15:49,540
Nothing left!

201
00:15:49,540 --> 00:15:51,110
We sucked 'em dry!

202
00:15:51,110 --> 00:15:55,910
That's what gets me: the very people who are
snotty about the disposability of pop will

