00:30:19,049 --> 00:30:21,809
'I've just finished the first half of Of Mice
and Men.'

415
00:30:21,809 --> 00:30:24,739
'What's the publication date of Of Mice and
Men?'...

416
00:30:24,739 --> 00:30:27,659
Still, it seemed like a good idea at the time.)

417
00:30:27,659 --> 00:30:31,129
I smiled politely, but the supposition mystified
me.

418
00:30:31,129 --> 00:30:33,390
Why on earth would I get excited?

419
00:30:33,390 --> 00:30:38,600
There had been interesting, sometimes even
enjoyable bits along the way - selling the

420
00:30:38,600 --> 00:30:43,350
rights to the book for an unfeasibly large
sum of money, for example, meeting the people

421
00:30:43,350 --> 00:30:47,769
responsible for the film version, seeing the
end product, which I liked a lot.

422
00:30:47,769 --> 00:30:54,470
I'd be very suspicious, however, of any writer
who was actually excited by any of this process,

423
00:30:54,470 --> 00:30:59,970
which can be on occasion distasteful (About
A Boy ate up a director and got spat out by

424
00:30:59,970 --> 00:31:06,430
another film company even before it was made)
and stupefying prolonged; indeed, the time

425
00:31:06,430 --> 00:31:11,889
before, during and after a film's release
is positively unpleasant.

426
00:31:11,889 --> 00:31:16,470
You get reviewed all over again; you discover
that half your friends never read the book

427
00:31:16,470 --> 00:31:21,340
in the first place; the bits of the film people
like the most turn out to be nothing to do

428
00:31:21,340 --> 00:31:22,690
with you.

429
00:31:22,690 --> 00:31:28,299
But the first time I heard the soundtrack
to the film really was exciting, in the proper,

430
00:31:28,299 --> 00:31:30,490
tingly sense of the word.

431
00:31:30,490 --> 00:31:35,539
Seeing one's words converted into Hollywood
cash is gratifying in all sorts of ways, but

432
00:31:35,539 --> 00:31:40,590
it really cannot compare to the experience
of hearing them converted into music: for

433
00:31:40,590 --> 00:31:45,919
someone who has to write books because he
cannot write songs, the idea that a book might

434
00:31:45,919 --> 00:31:50,369
somehow produce a song is embarrassingly thrilling.

435
00:31:50,369 --> 00:31:55,989
Like a lot of people, I spent a large chunk
of 2000 listening to and loving Badly Drawn

436
00:31:55,989 --> 00:31:58,970
Boy's The Hour of the Bewilder beast album.

437
00:31:58,970 --> 00:32:05,369
It's one of the very few English records of
recent years I've had any time for; it's thoughtful,

438
00:32:05,369 --> 00:32:10,889
quirky without being inept (despite my earlier
presumption that the name of the artist was

439
00:32:10,889 --> 00:32:15,809
somehow indicative of the ramshackle nature
of the music, a presumption that stopped me

440
00:32:15,809 --> 00:32:21,840
from listening to him for a while), it's melodic,
it borrows lightly and judiciously from all

441
00:32:21,840 --> 00:32:28,379
sorts of folky, rocky things I like (Damon
Gough is an early-Springsteen devotee), it

442
00:32:28,379 --> 00:32:33,379
doesn't show off, it is un-English in the
sense that it wouldn't be much use to Ibiza

443
00:32:33,379 --> 00:32:37,749
clubbers or boozed-up football hooligans,
it has soul.

444
00:32:37,749 --> 00:32:43,059
It also sounds cinematic, with its little
snatches of orchestration (it begins with

445
00:32:43,059 --> 00:32:48,630
a brass-band instrumental that would not have
sounded out of place in a gentle sixties comedy)

446
00:32:48,630 --> 00:32:50,529
and its range of moods.

447
00:32:50,529 --> 00:32:55,519
It seemed to me that Damon could write a wonderful
film score, and I would have suggested him

448
00:32:55,519 --> 00:33:01,279
for About A Boy had I not known that writers
have less chance of influencing film adaptations

449
00:33:01,279 --> 00:33:04,479
of their books than they do of changing the
weather.

450
00:33:04,479 --> 00:33:09,460
And then, the first time we met, Chris and
Paul Weitz, the co-directors, told me that

451
00:33:09,460 --> 00:33:13,859
they had already asked Damon to provide all
the music for the film.

452
00:33:13,859 --> 00:33:18,600
This struck me as being troublingly neat - could
it really be possible that the music in my

453
00:33:18,600 --> 00:33:20,809
head was the same as the music in theirs?

454
00:33:20,809 --> 00:33:26,860
- but anyway, here I am, in my office, listening
to a whole lot of new Badly Drawn Boy songs

455
00:33:26,860 --> 00:33:32,909
and music cues that very few people in the
world have heard yet, and feeling lucky.

456
00:33:32,909 --> 00:33:40,029
I began writing About A Boy in 1996, the year
my son Danny was finally diagnosed as autistic.

457
00:33:40,029 --> 00:33:46,269
There were lots of things to think (or panic,
or despair, or lose sleep) about, and money

458
00:33:46,269 --> 00:33:51,249
was only one of them, but I suddenly went
from feeling reasonably wealthy - I was in

459
00:33:51,249 --> 00:33:55,799
my fourth year of earning a decent whack from
writing, and for the first time in my life

460
00:33:55,799 --> 00:34:01,320
I had some savings - to financially vulnerable:
I was going to have to find enough to make

461
00:34:01,320 --> 00:34:06,379
sure that my son was secure, not just for
the duration of my life, but for the duration

462
00:34:06,379 --> 00:34:12,730
of his, and that extra thirty or forty years
was hard to contemplate, in more or less any

463
00:34:12,730 --> 00:34:13,770
direction.

464
00:34:13,770 --> 00:34:19,379
And then, no sooner had these worries begun
to take hold and chafe a little bit than this

465
00:34:19,379 --> 00:34:21,500
Hollywood money arrived.

466
00:34:21,500 --> 00:34:25,730
Until the movie was made, this was the only
connection I had forged between the book and

467
00:34:25,730 --> 00:34:26,730
Danny.

468
00:34:26,730 --> 00:34:32,389
The character of Marcus was nothing to do
with him (Marcus is twelve, and brightly voluble,

469
00:34:32,389 --> 00:34:38,280
if odd; Danny was three, and five years later
is still unable to speak), and I don't think

470
00:34:38,280 --> 00:34:42,560
that Danny would recognize the parenting that
Marcus experiences.

471
00:34:42,560 --> 00:34:46,840
It's possible that, if I had been child-less,
I would have been attracted to a different

472
00:34:46,840 --> 00:34:52,179
kind of story, but that's the only way that
About A Boy is about Danny.

473
00:34:52,179 --> 00:34:59,480
'A Minor Incident', a sweet, heartfelt, acoustic
strummer with a wheezy Dylanesque harmonica

474
00:34:59,480 --> 00:35:05,309
solo, refers directly to a major incident
in the book and the movie: Marcus comes home

475
00:35:05,309 --> 00:35:10,820
from a day out to discover his mother, Fiona,
lying comatose on the sofa after an attempt

476
00:35:10,820 --> 00:35:14,480
to kill herself, her vomit on the floor beside
her.

477
00:35:14,480 --> 00:35:17,340
The song is her suicide note to her son.

478
00:35:17,340 --> 00:35:22,340
I wrote one for her too, but it wasn't in
the form of a song lyric, and Damon's words

479
00:35:22,340 --> 00:35:26,000
capture Fiona's dippy, depressive insouciance
perfectly.

480
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:32,330
But here's the thing: once I'd listened to
'A Minor Incident' a couple of times, it started

481
00:35:32,330 --> 00:35:37,260
to make me think of Danny in ways that I hadn't
done when I was writing the book.

482
00:35:37,260 --> 00:35:42,700
'You always were the one to make us stand
out in a crowd I Though every once in a while

483
00:35:42,700 --> 00:35:48,280
your head was in a cloud I There's nothing
you could never do to ever let me down', sings

484
00:35:48,280 --> 00:35:51,120
Damon as Fiona, and the lines brought me up
short.

485
00:35:51,120 --> 00:35:57,630
Autistic children are by their nature the
dreamiest of kids, and Danny's ways of making

486
00:35:57,630 --> 00:36:02,710
us stand out in a crowd can include attempts
to steal strangers' crisps and to get undressed

487
00:36:02,710 --> 00:36:04,680
on the top of a number 19 bus.

488
00:36:04,680 --> 00:36:07,680
But that peculiar negative in the last line...

489
00:36:07,680 --> 00:36:13,910
How did Badly Drawn Boy know that it's the
things that Danny will never do (talk, read,

490
00:36:13,910 --> 00:36:18,750
play football, all sorts of stuff) that make
those who love him feel the most fiercely

491
00:36:18,750 --> 00:36:20,930
proud and protective of him?

492
00:36:20,930 --> 00:36:27,160
And, suddenly, five years on, I find a mournful
undertow of identification in the lyric to

493
00:36:27,160 --> 00:36:32,329
the song, because the money from the sale
of the film rights has forced me to contemplate

494
00:36:32,329 --> 00:36:37,440
my own mortality; like Fiona, I'm thinking
of a time when I won't be around for Danny

495
00:36:37,440 --> 00:36:41,280
- for different reasons, but the end result
is the same.

496
00:36:41,280 --> 00:36:43,740
So there we go.

497
00:36:43,740 --> 00:36:50,589
That's where the excitement lies: in the magical
coincidences and transferences of creativity.

498
00:36:50,589 --> 00:36:55,830
I write a book that isn't about my kid, and
then someone writes a beautiful song based

499
00:36:55,830 --> 00:37:00,500
on an episode in my book that turns out to
mean something much more personal to me than

500
00:37:00,500 --> 00:37:02,650
my book ever did.

501
00:37:02,650 --> 00:37:06,160
And I won't say that this sort of thing is
worth more than all the Hollywood money in

502
00:37:06,160 --> 00:37:11,380
the world, because I'm a pragmatist, and that
Hollywood money has given Danny a trust fund

503
00:37:11,380 --> 00:37:15,799
which will hopefully see him through those
terrifying thirty or forty years.

504
00:37:15,799 --> 00:37:22,599
But it's worth an awful lot, something money
can't buy, and it makes me want to keep writing

505
00:37:22,599 --> 00:37:28,049
and collaborating, in the hope that something
I write will strike this kind of dazzling,

506
00:37:28,049 --> 00:37:32,560
serendipitous spark off someone again.

507
00:37:32,560 --> 00:37:37,490
CHAPTER SIX
Caravan - Van Morrison

508
00:37:37,490 --> 00:37:42,840
The magnificent version of 'Caravan' on It's
Too Late to Stop Now (Van Morrison's most

509
00:37:42,840 --> 00:37:48,309
enjoyable album, unarguably, so don't even
think about arguing) sounds to me like it

510
00:37:48,309 --> 00:37:52,990
could be played over the closing credits of
the best film you've ever seen; and if something

511
00:37:52,990 --> 00:37:58,799
sounds like that to you, then surely by extension
it means that it could also be played at your

512
00:37:58,799 --> 00:38:00,390
own funeral.

513
00:38:00,390 --> 00:38:04,960
I don't think this is over-dramatizing the
importance of one's own life.

514
00:38:04,960 --> 00:38:09,970
Not all films have to be like Lawrence of
Arabia or Apocalypse Now, and you'd have to

515
00:38:09,970 --> 00:38:14,200
have been pretty unlucky, at least in our
part of the world (and if you walked into

516
00:38:14,200 --> 00:38:19,130
a bookshop and bought this book, you live
in the part I'm talking about), not to have

517
00:38:19,130 --> 00:38:25,770
experienced a few moments of joy or pure hope
or clenched-fist triumph or simple contentment

518
00:38:25,770 --> 00:38:29,390
amongst all the drudgery and heartbreak and
pain.

519
00:38:29,390 --> 00:38:35,579
To me, 'Cara-van' recognizes and synthesizes
all of it, and the fact that what it produces

520
00:38:35,579 --> 00:38:41,329
from the whole extraordinary mess is something
that sounds cheerful doesn't mean that the

521
00:38:41,329 --> 00:38:43,289
song is trite.

522
00:38:43,289 --> 00:38:48,490
'Caravan' isn't a song about life or death,
as far as I can tell: it's a song about merry

523
00:38:48,490 --> 00:38:52,839
gypsies and campfires and turning up your
radio and stuff.

524
00:38:52,839 --> 00:38:58,140
But in its long, vamped passage right before
the cli-max, when the sax weaves gently in

525
00:38:58,140 --> 00:39:03,880
and out of the cute, witty, neochamber strings,
while the piano sprinkles bluesy high notes

526
00:39:03,880 --> 00:39:10,299
over the top, Morrison's band seems to isolate
a moment somewhere between life and its aftermath,

527
00:39:10,299 --> 00:39:15,670
a big, baroque entrance hall of a place where
you can stop and think about everything that

528
00:39:15,670 --> 00:39:16,980
has gone before.

529
00:39:16,980 --> 00:39:17,980
(Gosh.

530
00:39:17,980 --> 00:39:22,940
A sudden panic: can you hear any of that,
those of you who already own the album or

531
00:39:22,940 --> 00:39:26,760
who are interested enough in this description
to check it out?

532
00:39:26,760 --> 00:39:27,760
Possibly not.

533
00:39:27,760 --> 00:39:33,450
But - panic over - this book isn't predicated
on you and me sharing the ability to hear

534
00:39:33,450 --> 00:39:38,380
exactly the same things; in other words, it
isn't music criticism.

535
00:39:38,380 --> 00:39:43,089
All I'm hoping here is that you have equivalents
that you spend a lot of time listening to

536
00:39:43,089 --> 00:39:46,140
music and seeing faces in its fire.)

537
00:39:46,140 --> 00:39:51,690
And, though it won't be me doing the thinking,
as far as we know, is it arrogant to expect

538
00:39:51,690 --> 00:39:54,530
a little reflection from friends and family?

539
00:39:54,530 --> 00:39:56,670
It's my funeral, after all.

540
00:39:56,670 --> 00:40:00,920
And they don't have to think only about me;
they can think about all sorts of things,

541
00:40:00,920 --> 00:40:05,779
as long as they're worthy of the occasion
and the music, and don't involve foodstuffs,

542
00:40:05,779 --> 00:40:08,500
emails, footwear, etc.

543
00:40:08,500 --> 00:40:13,920
The only thing that worries me about having
'Caravan' played at my funeral is that string

544
00:40:13,920 --> 00:40:14,920
section.

545
00:40:14,920 --> 00:40:19,460
Will people think I'm making some concession
to classical music when they hear it?

546
00:40:19,460 --> 00:40:23,529
Will they say to themselves, 'What a shame
he lost the courage of his convictions right

547
00:40:23,529 --> 00:40:26,140
at the end there, just like everybody else'?

548
00:40:26,140 --> 00:40:28,290
I wouldn't want them to think that.

549
00:40:28,290 --> 00:40:32,430
Unless something unimaginable happens to me
over the next couple of decades, I will have

550
00:40:32,430 --> 00:40:37,609
gone through an entire life listening more
or less only to popular music in one or other

551
00:40:37,609 --> 00:40:38,609
of its forms.

552
00:40:38,609 --> 00:40:44,750
(I have a few classical CDs, and sometimes
I play them, too; but I never respond to Mozart

553
00:40:44,750 --> 00:40:50,450
or Haydn as music, merely as something that
makes the room smell temporarily different,

554
00:40:50,450 --> 00:40:55,980
like a scented candle, and I don't like treating
art in that way, with disrespect.)

555
00:40:55,980 --> 00:40:57,920
And I'm unrepentant, too.

556
00:40:57,920 --> 00:41:02,869
'I'd see him banged up for having anything
to do with the inanity that is pop, full stop,'

557
00:41:02,869 --> 00:41:08,109
said a famously sour writer and newspaper
columnist recently, while attempting to defend

558
00:41:08,109 --> 00:41:12,640
a well-known music-business mogul who had
just been imprisoned, but you've heard this

559
00:41:12,640 --> 00:41:14,170
stuff before.

560
00:41:14,170 --> 00:41:19,440
I have no idea whether his use of the word
'pop' is the same as mine, whether he thinks

561
00:41:19,440 --> 00:41:23,990
that all of it, Dylan and Marvin Gaye and
Neil Young, is inane.

562
00:41:23,990 --> 00:41:25,619
I suspect he does.

563
00:41:25,619 --> 00:41:31,680
It's not a complaint I've ever understood,
because music, like colour, or a cloud, is

564
00:41:31,680 --> 00:41:35,780
neither intelligent nor unintelligent - it
just is.

565
00:41:35,780 --> 00:41:41,760
The chord, the simplest building-block for
even the tri test, silliest chart song, is

566
00:41:41,760 --> 00:41:49,170
a beautiful, perfect, mysterious thing, and
when an ill-read, uneducated, uncultured,

567
00:41:49,170 --> 00:41:53,660
emotionally illiterate boor puts a couple
of them together, he has every chance of creating

568
00:41:53,660 --> 00:41:56,280
something wonderful and powerful.

569
00:41:56,280 --> 00:42:01,609
I don't want to read inane books, but books
are built from words, our only instruments

570
00:42:01,609 --> 00:42:06,470
of thought; all I ask of music is that it
sounds good.

571
00:42:06,470 --> 00:42:12,020
Despite its crudity and simplicity, 'Twist
and Shout' sounds good - in fact, any attempt

572
00:42:12,020 --> 00:42:18,420
to sophisticate it would make it sound much
worse - and I fundamentally, profoundly disagree

573
00:42:18,420 --> 00:42:24,279
with anyone who equates musical complication
and intelligence with superiority.

574
00:42:24,279 --> 00:42:29,980
It doesn't work like that, which is maybe
why these people despise pop music, because

575
00:42:29,980 --> 00:42:32,130
it's one of the very few things that doesn't.

576
00:42:32,130 --> 00:42:34,930
(They often hate sports, too.)

577
00:42:34,930 --> 00:42:40,700
I don't dislike classical music because of
its cultivation - I'm not an inverted snob.

578
00:42:40,700 --> 00:42:47,510
I dislike it (or at least, I'm unaffected
by it) because it sounds churchy, and because,

579
00:42:47,510 --> 00:42:52,930
to my ears at least, it can't deal with the
smaller feelings that constitute a day and

580
00:42:52,930 --> 00:42:59,579
a week and a life, and because there are no
backing vocals or basslines or guitar solos,

581
00:42:59,579 --> 00:43:04,150
and because a lot of people who profess to
like it actually don't really like any music

582
00:43:04,150 --> 00:43:10,510
(or any culture) at all, and because I grew
up listening to something else, and because

583
00:43:10,510 --> 00:43:16,730
it does not possess the ability to make me
feel, and because I don't need my music to

584
00:43:16,730 --> 00:43:22,640
sound any 'better' than it does already - a
great, farting, squelching, quick-witted sax

585
00:43:22,640 --> 00:43:25,340
solo does the job for me.

586
00:43:25,340 --> 00:43:29,170
So 'Caravan' will be played at my funeral.

587
00:43:29,170 --> 00:43:33,720
The problem with the extended passage that
I mentioned earlier, the bit that I hope will

588
00:43:33,720 --> 00:43:36,829
make the mourners think and reflect is that...

589
00:43:36,829 --> 00:43:42,500
Well, OK, here's the thing: it's the bit where
Van Morrison introduces the band.

590
00:43:42,500 --> 00:43:44,569
'Terry Adams on cello...

591
00:43:44,569 --> 00:43:46,569
Nancy Ellis on viola...

592
00:43:46,569 --> 00:43:48,309
Bill Elwin on trumpet...

593
00:43:48,309 --> 00:43:50,460
David Hayes on bass...'

594
00:43:50,460 --> 00:43:51,780
Is that too weird?

595
00:43:51,780 --> 00:43:56,579
Can people really file out of my funeral listening
to a list of names of people they (and I)

596
00:43:56,579 --> 00:43:58,359
don't know?

597
00:43:58,359 --> 00:44:03,880
I've started to think of this passage as a
sort of metaphorical dramatis personae now:

598
00:44:03,880 --> 00:44:10,160
granted, I don't know David Hayes or Nancy
Ellis, but, you know... I probably knew someone

599
00:44:10,160 --> 00:44:11,470
like them.

600
00:44:11,470 --> 00:44:15,792
That's the best I can come up with, and it'll
have to do, because I'm not changing my mind,

601
00:44:15,792 --> 00:44:16,792
so there.

602
00:44:16,792 --> 00:44:16,794
- THE END -

